ussian Orthodox publicists launched a public relations campaign in the West, especially in France, in the 1850s and 1860s. The linchpin of their campaign was the building of the impressive Saint Alexander Nevskey Church in Paris, consecrated in 1861. Bailey posits that, as the embodiment of the belief that Russia had a great historical purpose imextricably tied to Orthodoxy, the Paris church both reflected and contributed to the rise of religious nationalism in Russia that followed the Crimean War. At the same time, the confrontation with westerners' negative ideas about the Eastern Church fueled a reformist spirit in Russia while contributing to a better understanding of Eastern Orthodoxy in the West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aPublic opinionzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic opinionzRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 4aFrance. 4aReligious Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aOrthodoxy, Catholicism, Russophobia, Franco-Russian relations, losif vasiliev.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501749537zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501749537423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501749537/original  a978-3-11-069046-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook